					<description><![CDATA[In reply to &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.g400.co.uk/cantabits/archives/825#comment-101&quot;&gt;Alastair&lt;/a&gt;.

I don&#039;t think it will automatically reinstall your apps - all of the apps you have ever downloaded are listed in a special place in (and are free to download from) Google Play (menu button -&gt; &quot;My Apps&quot; -&gt; &quot;All&quot;). However, when you do reinstall an app, your settings and data for that app should be restored if you have &quot;Back up my settings&quot; and &quot;Automatic restore&quot; checked in &quot;Settings&quot; -&gt; &quot;Personal&quot; -&gt; &quot;Backup &amp; reset&quot;. Unfortunately, as you can see from &lt;a href=&quot;http://developer.android.com/guide/topics/data/backup.html&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;the developer documentation for the backup feature&lt;/a&gt;, such functionality is not compulsory and there will certainly be some apps that don&#039;t use it.

I had thought that this feature would be taken advantage of by the Messages application for backing up SMS/MMS messages, but I don&#039;t think it does as it seems to offer its own &quot;Back up/Restore SMS&quot; option in its menu.

I guess there is no single relatively simple and guaranteed way of backing up and restoring everything on Android. :(]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>In reply to <a href="https://www.g400.co.uk/cantabits/archives/825#comment-101">Alastair</a>.</p>
<p>I don&#8217;t think it will automatically reinstall your apps &#8211; all of the apps you have ever downloaded are listed in a special place in (and are free to download from) Google Play (menu button -> &#8220;My Apps&#8221; -> &#8220;All&#8221;). However, when you do reinstall an app, your settings and data for that app should be restored if you have &#8220;Back up my settings&#8221; and &#8220;Automatic restore&#8221; checked in &#8220;Settings&#8221; -> &#8220;Personal&#8221; -> &#8220;Backup &#038; reset&#8221;. Unfortunately, as you can see from <a href="http://developer.android.com/guide/topics/data/backup.html" rel="nofollow">the developer documentation for the backup feature</a>, such functionality is not compulsory and there will certainly be some apps that don&#8217;t use it.</p>
<p>I had thought that this feature would be taken advantage of by the Messages application for backing up SMS/MMS messages, but I don&#8217;t think it does as it seems to offer its own &#8220;Back up/Restore SMS&#8221; option in its menu.</p>
<p>I guess there is no single relatively simple and guaranteed way of backing up and restoring everything on Android. üôÅ</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
