					<description><![CDATA[In reply to &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.g400.co.uk/cantabits/archives/825#comment-80&quot;&gt;Alastair&lt;/a&gt;.

I&#039;m curious - what was the clock/weather problem?

I haven&#039;t got much familiarity with Show Me, I&#039;m afraid - I&#039;ve just looked at it for the first time, and I recognise the videos from YouTube, so maybe try watching them there: http://www.youtube.com/user/HTCShowMe/videos. With all of the factory resets I&#039;ve done (I&#039;ve done all sorts of things with phones for research and work purposes), I&#039;ve never lost any data - the phone is normally capable of restoring everything on its internal memory to its original state and the rest of the storage (the 25GB internal partition on the One X, the microSD card on phones that have them) is left alone by the process, in my experience. Have you tried looking for the original data on the xda-developers forum? That normally has everything you need when things go wrong.

I haven&#039;t seen any Tasks problems personally - that&#039;s one of my favourite apps. Driver installation can be tricky, but I agree that HTC&#039;s software for non-mobile operating systems is poor. There are also thousands of apps for backing up data on Google Play, and ClockworkMod Recovery (http://forum.xda-developers.com/wiki/ClockworkMod_Recovery) provides backup and restore facilities that bypass the need for Android to be present or working at all, though I think the best method is Android&#039;s built-in backup facility (there&#039;s a vaguely approachable tool for using it here: http://forum.xda-developers.com/showthread.php?t=1844032).

Indeed, it is a shame that your phone has such annoying issues. One drastic option would be to install plain Android on it (though that&#039;s not guaranteed to be any less buggy): http://forum.xda-developers.com/showthread.php?t=1786696]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>In reply to <a href="https://www.g400.co.uk/cantabits/archives/825#comment-80">Alastair</a>.</p>
