		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Alastair]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Wed, 07 Nov 2012 13:40:44 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://twitter-265224515917848577-post#comment-80</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[I am starting to wonder about the HTC One X I have had lots of issues with it in the short time I have owned mine.

The advice I always get is to do a factory reset, out of the three problems I have reported this has only worked on one so far! But, it seems to be a standard response? It is very time consuming and shouldn&#039;t really be necessary if the phone had, had all the issues sorted before it was put on the market. The phone; an HTC One X has had 3 software related problems already, I have only had it approx 2 months!

1. Fault with clock/weather HTC app - solved satisfactorily with factory reset.

2. Fault with &quot;Show Me&quot; HTC app - This one still hasn&#039;t been explained satisfactorily, factory reset, cache clear and storage delete was the advice given to me, however didn&#039;t help one bit! A few days later the issue suddenly cured itself, but as a result of the above advice a lot of data (supplied with the phone was irrecoverably lost) and HTC were unable or unwilling to supply the missing files saying they weren&#039;t available? How do they copy this data to every new phone manufactured then?

3. Fault with &quot;Tasks&quot; HTC app duplicating entries in the calendar - still to be resolved... I haven&#039;t had time to do another Factory reset yet and I am fed up with losing all my data, apps and customisations every time! Also, I was advised to install &quot;Sync manager&quot; on my phone to backup it up - I spent a whole night trying to install it because it kept failing, refusing to find the correct drivers (bad programming I suspect) eventually I had to e-mail support again to get this solved, but it was not a neat solution having to install an earlier bit of software made by HTC and cancel the install once the drivers had loaded - why?? - This looks very unprofessional, not what I was expecting from HTC at all!

It&#039;s a real shame as the phone is great most of the time... Just getting fed up with having to re-install all my settings every time I have a software issue! Feeling like a Guinea pig for HTC right now!]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I am starting to wonder about the HTC One X I have had lots of issues with it in the short time I have owned mine.</p>
<p>The advice I always get is to do a factory reset, out of the three problems I have reported this has only worked on one so far! But, it seems to be a standard response? It is very time consuming and shouldn&#8217;t really be necessary if the phone had, had all the issues sorted before it was put on the market. The phone; an HTC One X has had 3 software related problems already, I have only had it approx 2 months!</p>
<p>1. Fault with clock/weather HTC app &#8211; solved satisfactorily with factory reset.</p>
<p>2. Fault with &#8220;Show Me&#8221; HTC app &#8211; This one still hasn&#8217;t been explained satisfactorily, factory reset, cache clear and storage delete was the advice given to me, however didn&#8217;t help one bit! A few days later the issue suddenly cured itself, but as a result of the above advice a lot of data (supplied with the phone was irrecoverably lost) and HTC were unable or unwilling to supply the missing files saying they weren&#8217;t available? How do they copy this data to every new phone manufactured then?</p>
<p>3. Fault with &#8220;Tasks&#8221; HTC app duplicating entries in the calendar &#8211; still to be resolved&#8230; I haven&#8217;t had time to do another Factory reset yet and I am fed up with losing all my data, apps and customisations every time! Also, I was advised to install &#8220;Sync manager&#8221; on my phone to backup it up &#8211; I spent a whole night trying to install it because it kept failing, refusing to find the correct drivers (bad programming I suspect) eventually I had to e-mail support again to get this solved, but it was not a neat solution having to install an earlier bit of software made by HTC and cancel the install once the drivers had loaded &#8211; why?? &#8211; This looks very unprofessional, not what I was expecting from HTC at all!</p>
<p>It&#8217;s a real shame as the phone is great most of the time&#8230; Just getting fed up with having to re-install all my settings every time I have a software issue! Feeling like a Guinea pig for HTC right now!</p>
